Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

  1. Whats gone wrong with this code? Why are the points not blue?

    library(ggplot2)
    ## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.2.5
    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

    Answer: The positioning of the parenthesis is causing the mapping function to look for an attribute called blue in the data. The color selection must be moved outside the parenthisis.

     library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "blue")

  2. Which variables in mpg are categorical? Which variables are continuous? (Hint: type ?mpg to read the documentation for the dataset). How can you see this information when you run mpg?

    Answer: model, cyl, trans, drv, fl, and class are categorical

    ?mpg

  3. Map a continuous variable to color, size, and shape. How do these aesthetics behave differently for categorical vs.continuous variables?

    Answer:

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = cty))

  4. What happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics?

    Answer: Nothing breaks, but you do get unnecessary redundency in terms of information display

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ,size=displ))

  5. What does the stroke aesthetic do? What shapes does it work with? (Hint: use ?geom_point)

    Answer: stroke lets us set a different fill color and outer stroke color and width

    ggplot(mtcars, aes(disp, mpg,color=cyl))+
geom_point(shape = 21, fill = "white", size = 5, stroke =5)

  6. What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = displ < 5)?

    Answer: Mappping an aesthetic with a cutoff value lets us redefine visually break points inside a given set of variables (e.g.showing all cars with a displacement of less than 5 liters in a different color from those at or above 5 liters)

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ<5,size=displ))

Exercise 2

  1. What do the empty cells in plot with facet_grid(drv ~ cyl) mean? How do they relate to this plot?

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

    Answer: The empty cells indicate that there were no vehicles with a given combination of attributes (e.g.there were no 4 cylinder rear wheel drive vehicles in the dataset)

  2. What plots does the following code make? What does . do?

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

    Answer: The first plot makes a facet grid in which each plot compares the displacement and highway MPGs of vehicles within categories based on drivetrain visualized as rows. The second plot makes a faced grid in which each plot compares the displacement and highway MPGs of vehicles within categories based on the number of cylinders the vehicle has visualized in columns. The . allows us to categorize the plots based on a single variable rather than requiring that all plots be X by X

  3. Take the first faceted plot in this section:

    ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

    What are the advantages to using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic? What are the disadvantages? How might the balance change if you had a larger dataset?

    Answer: advantages: Using faceting declutters the visualization and enables the viewer to focus on comparisons within a single vehicle category more easily. disadvantages: Using faceting makes comparisons between vehicle categories more challenging and can slow cognitive processing by requiring the user to look at multiple plots rather than a single visualization.

  1. What geom would you use to draw a line chart? A boxplot? A histogram? An area chart?

  2. Run this code in your head and predict what the output will look like. Then, run the code in R and check your predictions.

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

    Answer: Prediction: I expect to see points colored by drivetrain with displacement for x coordinates and highway MPGs for y coordinates. I expect to see an overlaid regression line of displacement vs.Highway MPG for each drivetrain category, color coded the same as the points.

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

  3. What does show.legend = FALSE do? What happens if you remove it?
    Why do you think I used it earlier in the chapter?

    Answer: show.legend=FALSE (or the null) allow us to remove or display the legend for the visual encoding of a given layer of a visualization

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE,show.legend=FALSE)
    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

  4. What does the se argument to geom_smooth() do?

    Answer: The se argument either allows or removes the standard error shaded region on a line plot

  5. Will these two graphs look different? Why/why not?

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

    Answer: They should look exactly the same because the only difference is where the author is deciding to define elements that are common to both layers of each plot.

  6. Recreate the R code necessary to generate the following graphs.

    Smooth lines for each drv

    Answer:

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE,color="blue",mapping=aes(linetype=drv))
    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

    A single smooth line, transparency by year

    Answer:

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv,alpha=year)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(color="blue",se=FALSE,show.legend=FALSE)
    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

    Layered dots and an additional text information

    Adding texts was not covered in class, but give it a try!

    Answer:

    ggplot(data = mpg,mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, fill=drv)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 21, color="white", size = 2, stroke =2)

Exercise 4

  1. What is the default geom associated with stat_summary()? How could you rewrite the previous plot to use that geom function instead of the stat function?

    Answer: The default geometry is pointrange

    ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_pointrange(
mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
stat="summary",
fun.ymin = min,
fun.ymax = max,
fun.y = median
  )

  2. What does geom_col() do? How is it different to geom_bar()?

    Answer: geom_col sets the bar heights of bars to the raw values in your dataset. geom_bar uses a counter to make the hight of bars the number of appearances of a particular value in your dataset.

  3. What variables does stat_smooth() compute? What parameters control its behaviour?

    Answer: stat_smooth computes y, ymin, ymax, and standard error. It is controled by the method of smoothing (method), the binary value for plotting the standard error (se) and the desired confidence level (level)

    ?stat_smooth

Exercise 5

  1. What is the problem with this plot? How could you improve it? Some points plot over the top of each other. This could be solved with alpha or jitter

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.5,position="jitter")

    Answer:

  2. What parameters to geom_jitter() control the amount of jittering?

    Answer: amount of jittering is controled by the width and height parameters in the position argument

    ?geom_jitter

  3. Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count().

    Answer: geom_jitter moves overlapping points slightly. geom_count modifies the size of a plotted pont in proportion to the number of overplots at that location

    ?geom_count

Exercise 6

  1. Turn a stacked bar chart into a pie chart using coord_polar().

    Answer:

    #?coord_plot
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = factor(1), fill = drv)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y")+
  labs(title="I made this pie chart about drive type, \n even though I hate pie charts")

  2. What does labs() do? Read the documentation.

    Answer: labs() lets you add title, subtitle, and add X and Y labels

    ?labs()

  3. What does the plot below tell you about the relationship between city and highway mpg? Why is coord_fixed() important? What does geom_abline() do?

    ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

    Answer: We learn that cars city and highway mileage are linearly related and that cars get slightly better highway mpg

geom_abline adds a reference line that by default has a slope of 1 and an intercept of 0. coord_fixed sets the inervals on the x and y axes to be equal, allowing for undistorted comparisons

?coord_fixed()
